Consider the following: You read a (probably long) Confluence page and while reading you decide to edit this Confluence page. In stead of scrolling up to the top of the page and click "edit" you might use the "e" keyboard shortcut. But the courser in the editor always starts on top of the page and you have to navigate to the line you want to edit again.

In order to save searching/scrolling time it would be desirable if the edit courser starts roughly at the position where the editing mode was triggered.

h3. Issue Summary
When using the *Insert Page* macro on a page that contains a table with colored cells, it doesn't keep the cells' colors in the page we use the macro.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Create a new page;
# Add simple table;
# Fill some of the cells with text (not all of them);
# Paint some of the cells with green, for example;
# Publish the page;
# Create a new page;
# Call the *Include Page* macro and set it to get the first page we created here;
# Publish the page.

h3. Expected Results
The from the first page is embedded well in the new page.
h3. Actual Results
The content lost its formatting and the table comes as if it was in the old editor - plus, it is not colored

h3. Workaround
On the first page, place the content within the *Excerpt* macro. Then, on the second page, insert the *Excerpt Include* macro, pointing to the first page.

h3. Summary
When using a *Page Properties Report* macro, if our screen/browser width is too small to have the entire macro's columns showed up in the screen, the columns get wrapped, splitting the words into two lines.

h3. Steps to reproduce
# Create a page *A* and add a *Page Properties* macro with some content within it, making sure to some columns;
# Publish this page;
# Create a page *B*;
# Add a *Page Properties Report* macro, pointing to page *A*;
# Publish the page;
# Change the browser's width to get it smaller.

h3. Expected Results
The *Page Properties Report* macro is adjusted to be scrolled to the right side, in order to keep the integrity of the data it is showing.

h3. Actual results
The macro gets its columns wrapped, splitting the words.

h3. Workaround
If you use a monitor that is smaller enough to be affected for this issue, apply a zoom out on your browser window until the content gets healthy.

h3. Issue Summary
While creating or editing a template, the placeholder text box is canceled if we switch between the browser's tabs - which leads us to lose all the content we had inserted so far.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Go to *Settings > Global Templates and Blueprints*;
# Click over *Add global page template*;
# From the editor's toolbar, click on the *+* icon and select the *Placeholder Text* option;
# Insert a word;
# Switch to another browser tab;
# Back to Confluence's tab.
 [^CONFCLOUD-68783.mp4] 

h3. Expected Results
The placeholder text box is there.
h3. Actual Results
The placeholder text box is gone.

h3. Workaround
Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

h3. *Current Situation*
{panel:titleColor=#fff5e6|titleBGColor=#4da9ff|borderColor=#4d2800|borderStyle=dashed|bgColor=#e6f3ff}




The current Confluence Advanced Search provides users with limited fields for them to look for pages/spaces. It would be useful to provide users with the ability to configure the fields that they're looking for, instead of providing default fixed ones.


 !Screen Shot 2019-12-03 at 10.35.13.png|thumbnail! 

*Screenshot*: _Users cannot choose which field they'd like to search for, besides these default ones_
{panel}

h3. *Proposed Solution*
{panel:titleColor=#fff5e6|titleBGColor=#4da9ff|borderColor=#4d2800|borderStyle=dashed|bgColor=#e6f3ff}




(/) A suggestion, to improve this search would be to provide users with the ability to use CQL ([Advanced searching using CQL|https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/confluence/advanced-searching-using-cql/]) via the UI. 

This would provide users with the same flexibility as Jira to search for pages, spaces, labels.

(i) e.g. User would like to look for the creator of a page, however, the field *Creator* is not present on advanced search and using the default *Contributors* field also returns pages that were edited by said user, making this field not particularly useful for this situation.
{panel}
